This is a test script that allows you to test the use of the "Dialogue Branch External Variable Service Dummy" application.

[[Whoah?! What is that all about?|ExplainVarService]]
[[Okay, let's do the test.|Test]]
===
title: ExplainVarService
tags: 
speaker: Martin McOwl
colorID: 0
position: 277,103
---
In Dialogue Branch, there are many ways you can cleverly use variables to make dialogues more personalized or interactive.

[[Explain2]]
===
title: Explain2
tags: 
speaker: Martin McOwl
colorID: 2
position: 276,-163
---
<<set $varServiceExplained = "This is a variable" >>

Variables may be defined within the dialogue script, like we set the 'varServiceExplained' variable right now, and the value is "$varServiceExplained".

[[Explain3]]
===
title: Explain3
tags: 
speaker: Martin McOwl
colorID: 0
position: 280,-408
---
But sometimes you need to collect data from an 'external' source, like a weather API, or your own user database.

[[Explain4]]
===
title: Explain4
tags: 
speaker: Martin McOwl
colorID: 0
position: 277,-659
---
That is what the 'Dialogue Branch External Variable Service' is for. It allows you to connect the Web Service to an external source of variable data, which you can build yourself to provide whatever data you like.

[[Explain5]]
===
title: Explain5
tags: 
speaker: Martin McOwl
colorID: 0
position: 278,-926
---
Does that make a sense?

[[Please, explain me again.|ExplainVarService]]
[[Yes, let's run the test.|Test]]
===
title: Test
tags: 
speaker: Martin McOwl
colorID: 0
position: 548,105
---
Okay, the following information should be provided by the Dummy implementation of the External Variable Service. The current date is $currentDate, and the current time is $currentTime.
